<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 94 / The Liberal Democrats in Brighton: Lib-Lab pact talks may
start next year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, has begun to sketch out his
terms for a future partnership with Labour, believing the parties could
combine to defeat the Tories at the next election.
Mr Ashdown has been unwilling to publicly discuss relations with other
parties at this week's conference. But he is understood to believe that Mr
Tony Blair's election as Labour leader has created an opportunity to
transform the landscape of British politics.
Amid clear divisions within his own party and serious doubts over Labour's
response, the Liberal Democrat leader is determined not to rush into the
arms of Mr Blair.
But he has set out a series of conditions which Labour must meet before he
would consider serious co-operation. They include unequivocal backing for
proportional representation, a stance the Labour leader has so far refused
to adopt.
There is acknowledgement too among senior party figures that the extent of
any rapprochement will depend on the attitude which Labour adopts towards
the Liberal Democrats.
They demand that Labour local councillors must co-operate with their Liberal
Democrat counterparts, abandoning the alliances they have made with Tory
candidates in some town halls.
There is also an insistence that Labour must make clear its commitment to
political 'pluralism' and the principle that it will back the policies of
other parties.
If there is movement on these issues, Mr Ashdown does not rule out the
possibility that the parties could begin informal contacts on tactics and
policies next summer.
One possibility might be for the Liberal Democrats to indicate support for
particular items of legislation put down by a Labour government.
To this end, Mr Ashdown is understood to have asked Mr Charles Kennedy,
outgoing Liberal Democrat president, to examine whether the parties could
join forces in areas including constitutional reform and the promotion of
social justice legislation.
But Mr Ashdown is also understood to believe that there is scope to create a
more formal pact with Labour in the longer term, which could involve joint
selection of parliamentary candidates. In the event of a hung parliament
Liberal Democrat MPs could be included in a Labour cabinet.
In a speech to the party conference yesterday, Mr Kennedy also hinted that
the party leadership was developing a strategy of wooing Labour while
setting out clear conditions for co-operation.
He said that within the Liberal Democrat party 'there is the capacity to be
complimentary over other leaders'. He said: 'Pluralism in politics is a good
goal,' but 'you can only guarantee that goal by proportional
representation'.
Labour leaders have refused to entertain any idea of co-operation with Mr
Ashdown.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
</IN>
