<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 94 / The Liberal Democrats in Brighton: Power-sharing for Ulster
backed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Delegates approved a new policy statement on Northern Ireland in spite of
continuing doubts over the permanence of the ceasefire declared by the IRA.
The statement called for a power-sharing executive in Ulster, with
cross-border agencies providing an 'Irish dimension'.
Lord Holme, who played a leading role in framing the new policy, urged the
US authorities to join the British government in pressing for further
clarification.
He suggested that they should 'squeeze out' of Mr Gerry Adams, leader of
Sinn Fein, the word permanent or something akin to it before granting him
another visa.
A sharply contrasting view was expressed by Ms Mary Harney, leader of the
Progressive Democrats in the Irish Republic. In her role as guest speaker Ms
Harney said she had concluded that, even if the IRA was engaging in a
face-saving exercise, it would be 'ungenerous and churlish' not to recognise
that lives were still being saved.
Mr John Roberts, chairman of the party's Northern Ireland policy working
group, replied that it would be 100 times harder to achieve a long-term
settlement than it had been to win a ceasefire.
</TEXT>
