<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 94 / Reuters calls for trading to be open
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Reuters Holdings, the international information and news provider, has
joined the lobbying for securities regulators to insist on greater
transparency for trading on the London Stock Exchange.
The Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief regulatory watchdog,
has asked market participants whether the exchange should alter rules which
allow long delays before the markets generally are told about large
transactions.
Also, the SIB is questioning whether marketmakers who deal with each other
anonymously via inter-dealer broker screens ought to have their deals made
public.
In the US, Reuters was instrumental in persuading the Justice Department to
require inter-dealer brokers in US government bonds to make their prices
available to the public via information providers such as Reuters itself.
Reuters is the parent company for several information providers such as
Instinet, which in the US has gained significant market share from the New
York Stock Exchange by acting as a bulletin board for the buyers and sellers
of shares.
In a long submission to the SIB from officials at its Instinet subsidiary,
Reuters argues that lack of transparency has raised transactions costs,
effectively discouraging the growth of so-called quantitative fund
management in the UK.
</TEXT>
