<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 94 / Mortgage lenders to identify charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Borrowers should be given clearer information about the valuation and
administration fees which mortgage lenders charge, the Council of Mortgage
Lenders said yesterday, Alison Smith writes.
The council's decision followed pressure from the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission, which reported in the spring that competition was being
distorted by the failure of some lenders to tell borrowers about the
administration fees that might be included with valuation fees.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, the director-general of fair trading, said lenders would
now identify separately their charges for arranging a mortgage and the
payments to surveyors to valuations.
The MMC inquiry began more than two years ago after complaints that lenders
refused to take valuations from independent surveyors and used only small
lists of approved valuers.
Sir Bryan said that in a separate move the council had also adopted an MMC
proposal that where a lender would accept valuations only from certain
valuers this should be made apparent at an early stage.
</TEXT>
