<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 94 / Rail talks start today as employers cope with disruption
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent and RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Negotiations will start today in moves to resolve the three-month rail
signal workers' dispute.
Officials from Acas, the independent conciliation service, held talks
yesterday at the headquarters of both the RMT transport union and Railtrack,
the state-owned company responsible for administering the network's
infrastructure.
The decision to restart talks follows Monday's decision by the RMT executive
to back a return to the negotiating table.
Union officials insist that there must be two sets of negotiations in
parallel. One would deal for the first time with the complex and
far-reaching restructuring package designed to modernise the work of the
signal workers. The other would be concerned with the union's original pay
claim for an 11 per cent wage increase for its signalling members for past
efficiency achievements.
Railtrack would have preferred the RMT to call off Friday's planned one-day
strike as a sign of goodwill but the company did not make this a condition
for the start of the negotiations.
The company is also unhappy about the RMT's decision to hold 48 hours of
disruption from September 29 and it hopes at least an interim deal can be
ready before the end of next week.
A survey of 200 central London employers has found that a third of them have
had production disrupted by the strike, Richard Donkin writes.
Most, however, have been learning to live with the strike, the Institute of
Personnel and Development, which carried out the survey, says.
Only 6 per cent of the employers said the strike had significantly affected
their operations; 30 per cent reported some effect and 63 per cent said
disruption was minimal.
Employees are also finding ways of circumventing the strike disruption. At
the beginning of the strike more than 13 per cent of the survey companies'
employees failed to get to work. The proportion has now fallen to 3 per
cent.
The most popular methods used by companies to minimise disruption involve
allowing staff to work from home, practised by 75 per cent of companies in
the survey; providing overnight accommodation, adopted by 43 per cent; and
providing buses for employees, used by 18 per cent.
Some 43 per cent of the employers were compensating staff for extra costs
incurred in getting to work. Half of the employers, however, expected staff
who found themselves strike-bound to take their absence as annual leave.
</TEXT>
