FT  21 SEP 94 / Alcohol retailers lobby for halving of duty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Beer drinker Kenneth Clarke will today meet a delegation from the Brewers
and Licensed Retailers Association, representing brewers and pub operators.
The delegation will ask the chancellor for a 50 per cent cut in beer duty in
November's Budget, Neil Buckley writes.
Brewers argue that only a cut of this size will solve the problem of
cross-Channel beer imports, now running at about 1m pints a day. The UK has
the second-highest duty regime in the European Union. The delegation, led by
Mr Ian Prosser, chairman of Bass, and Sir Paul Nicholson, chairman of Vaux
Group, will argue that a 50 per cent cut would not only lead to a recovery
in the beer market but would stimulate other associated revenues from the
industry - including other drinks duty, licence duty, value added tax and
corporation tax. This would lead, they say, to a Pounds 300m increase in
government revenues by 1997.
