<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 94 / Hume asks Clinton to grant trade concessions for Ulster
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Financial Times Reporter and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Hume, leader of the Social Democratic and Labour party, said
yesterday after meeting Mr Bill Clinton, US president, in Washington that he
had asked for a new trade agreement between the US and Northern Ireland.
Mr Hume said before talks which included Mr Al Gore, the vice-president: 'I
am not just asking for money . . . I have specific interesting proposals to
help us with economic regeneration.' The proposals are believed to cover
duty-free entry to the US for some goods made in Northern Ireland and the
border counties of the Irish Republic and new tax arrangements for small
businesses to help boost exports.
Mr Hume is the first Irish politician to meet the president in Washington
since the IRA ceasefire. A party of Ulster Unionist MPs is leaving for the
US today while Mr Gerry Adams, president of Sinn Fein, yesterday applied for
a visa. Mr Adams is to meet Senate foreign relations committee members next
month. Meetings are also likely with House of Representatives' members.
Mr Adams said on Channel 4 News last night that Mr John Major had shown by
his behaviour over Northern Ireland that he was a 'Tom Fool'. He said Mr
Major was 'playing with words' in demanding that the IRA add the word
'permanent' to its ceasefire declaration.
George Graham in Washington writes: Senator Christopher Dodd, a Democrat
from Connecticut, met Mr Hume yesterday and is to meet unionists today. 'It
is very important that Congress and the executive branch be seen as
even-handed,' he said. 'My own view is that in the long term it's going to
be private-sector investment in Northern Ireland that is the most successful
catalyst for peace and stability.'
Mr Richard Holbrooke, assistant secretary of state for European affairs,
told a congressional sub-committee yesterday that a decision on further aid
to Ireland was likely next month.
Power-sharing backed, Page 9
</TEXT>
