FT  21 SEP 94 / Brazil intervenes in currency markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Brazil's central bank yesterday intervened in the foreign exchange markets
for the first time since the July launch of a new currency, the Real, Angus
Foster writes. The bank was reported to be buying moderate quantities of
dollars in return for Reals.
The move follows mounting concern that the Real is overvalued against the US
dollar, having appreciated nearly 15 per cent since July.
