</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Antonio Gava (left), a former Christian Democrat interior minister and an
important political figure in Naples, was yesterday arrested on charges of
alleged association with the Camorra, the Neapolitan Mafia. The arrest was
one of 76 ordered by Naples magistrates on charges of association with the
Camorra. As interior minister from 1988-92, Mr Gava had direct control over
the fight against the Mafia. Earlier in 1987 as finance minister he had
responsibility for the Guardia di Finanza, the financial police. Mr Gava is
alleged to have developed his Camorra links in the early 1980s in the wake
of the transfer of vast funds to Naples and the surrounding region to make
good the damage caused by the devastating Irpinia earthquake. These funds
were diverted for political use and business investment which required Mafia
protection, the magistrates allege. In return for such protection the
politicians, allegedly headed by Mr Gava, provided political cover for the
Camorra. Yesterday Mr Gava's lawyer expressed surprise at the arrest and
claimed the charges were unspecific and lacked foundation.
