<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 94 / Bonds and stocks fall amid fears of inflation: US trade gap
widens; Wall Street and European markets drop sharply
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT and FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
World bond and stock markets fell yesterday after worse-than- expected US
trade figures and mounting concerns about the outlook for inflation and
interest rates in Europe and the US.
The immediate spur was US Commerce Department figures showing that the US
trade balance deteriorated significantly in July and recorded the
second-largest monthly deficit ever for trade in goods. The data added to
market fears about inflation prospects in the US and sharply depressed US
bonds and stocks.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average plunged 67.63 in a broadly based retreat to
3,869.09. In the Treasury market, foreign investors sold heavily in response
to fears of a weaker dollar, with the US and Japan preparing for a fresh
round of trade talks. Bonds managed to recoup some losses during the
afternoon.
Late in the New York trading session, the benchmark 30-year government issue
was down  7/32 at 96 25/32 , raising the cost of long-term finance.
Meanwhile, the dollar fell against the yen in European and US markets. By
late afternoon in New York, the dollar was quoted at Y97.675, down from
Y98.51 late on Monday.
The falls exacerbated a broader slide in most European bond and equity
markets. Economists emphasised that the underlying reason for the retreat
was not so much the US trade figures but a growing fear in European and US
markets that US inflation pressures are mounting while the European interest
rate cycle is likely to rise.
The FT-SE 100 share index fell 41.8 points to close at 3,037.3. UK
government bonds also fell sharply in the morning, with the December gilt
contract touching a low of 97.50 before rebounding at the end of the day to
close at 98.03, down from the opening price of 98.15.
Short sterling futures were also weak amid heavy trading. Meanwhile, yields
on 10-year government bonds also rose through the psychologically important
level of 9 per cent.
The declines were reflected in most European markets, where stock markets in
the Netherlands and Germany fell by about 1 per cent. European bonds also
had a volatile day, further strained by concerns that German money supply
figures, expected today, might be worse than expected.
The main factor driving the equity markets' fall, economists said, was the
volatility in international bond markets, where dealers apparently remain
unconvinced about governments' ability to maintain low inflation.
Mr Keith Skeoch, chief economist at UK brokers James Capel, said: 'The fall
in the Footsie is being generated as much by international factors as from
domestic figures.'
Broader inflation concerns, economists said, were likely to continue to
depress UK gilts in spite of the UK government's interest rate rise last
week. With the UK company results season now coming to an end, gilt markets
are expected to act as the key factor driving equity markets in the month
ahead.
Mr George Magnus, international economist at brokers SG Warburg in London,
said: 'There is a feeling in the markets that we have now crossed the
Rubicon, and what we have seen in the US in terms of rising inflation and
interest rates is migrating over to Europe now.'
Meanwhile, Mr Michael Saunders, UK economist at Salomon Brothers, said: 'It
is a combination of growth coming out stronger than expected, further upward
pressure on US rates and a sense that the German interest rate cycle has
changed.'
US trade gap, Page 6
Lex, Page 22
Bonds, Page 31
Currencies, Page 33
World stocks, Page 39
London stocks, Page 42
