<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 94 / Tensions rise in Haiti as police kill demonstrator: Aristide
refuses to acknowledge Carter accord with junta
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and JAMES HARDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, PORT-AU-PRINCE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The first signs of the difficulties facing US efforts to restore democracy
in Haiti came yesterday as the republic's police clubbed to death a
demonstrator welcoming the Americans.
Riot police used clubs and rifle butts to break up a crowd of thousands of
supporters of exiled President Jean-Bertrand Aristide at the port, leaving
several injured. According to US soldiers a Haitian policeman was shot and
wounded by a civilian.
US troops, who had been instructed not to intervene in domestic policing,
looked on. The clash raised fears about the conduct of Haiti's militia just
as the Clinton administration set out to win broader support for the deal it
reached with the Haitian junta on Sunday.
In Washington, General John Shalikashvili, chairman of the US joint chiefs
of staff, said troops would not intervene unless 'this level of violence
becomes so great that it threatens the overall stability and security of our
multinational forces'.
The incident apart, US deployment was greeted peacefully as troops spread
through the country and marines took over the northern city of Cap Haitien.
Gen Shalikashvili, who insisted Haitian troops were continuing to
co-operate, defended Sunday's agreement, which provides for General Raoul
Cedras and other military leaders to leave power, but not necessarily the
country, by October 15.
He said Pentagon officers would brief Mr Aristide on their plans for
occupying Haiti. Mr Aristide reaffirmed his commitment to last year's broken
Governor's Island Agreement - under which Gen Cedras had promised to leave
power a year ago - but ignoring the latest deal, arranged by former
president Jimmy Carter.
The ousted Haitian president said he would 'remain vigilant to the
declaration of democracy expressed by the people of Haiti, as together with
the people of Haiti we move toward a new beginning'. But Mr Aristide's
advisers said the omission of any endorsement of the new agreement was
deliberate. Mr Aristide was also said to be uneasy that the US had not
started to disarm the Haitian military.
Briefing congressional leaders at the White House, Mr Clinton said: 'This is
a very different and a much better day than it would have been had we not
been able to successfully combine the credible threat of force with
diplomacy.' He added that Washington 'must be prepared for the risks that
remain for the troops, but we should recognise that we are in a much
stronger and safer position to achieve our goals in Haiti today'.
Members of Congress from both parties remained sceptical about the chances
of restoring democracy to Haiti, and unhappy about the prospect that US
troops would have to remain in large numbers, probably until at least
February.
Priest in exile, Page 6
</TEXT>
