<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 94 / Michelin bounces back into profit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Michelin, the world's largest tyre manufacturer, bounced back into the black
in the first half of 1994, reporting a net profit of FFr410m (Pounds 49m)
after minority interests compared with a loss of FFr3.19bn last time.
The result reflected a recovery in the European car market after the sharp
recession of 1993 and the effects of the French group's restructuring
programme, Mr Eric Bourdais de Charbonniere, finance director, said.
Michelin's rationalisation plan launched in 1993 aims to cut costs by
FFr3.5bn by the middle of next year. The workforce has been cut to about
120,000 from 129,000 at the beginning of 1993. Salary costs have fallen from
43.5 per cent of sales to 39.7 per cent.
'The results show we are on the right course', Mr Bourdais de Charbonniere
said. 'But they mark only the beginning of the re-establishment of the
financial situation'. It had taken FFr310m of provisions to cover further
staffing changes in France.
He cited continued growth in the US market and recovery in Europe as the
factors behind a rise in sales from FFr30.6bn to FFr33.27bn. In both
markets, however, the benefit to profits was restrained by the relative
strength of sales of original equipment tyres, which are sold directly to
manufacturers, as opposed to higher margin replacement tyres which are sold
to individuals.
In the US, the company expects the combined operations of Michelin and
Uniroyal Goodrich, acquired in 1990, to break even this year. After tough
negotiations with the United Rubber Workers union, Michelin said it had
implemented more efficient shifts.
Volume growth of 13 per cent in Europe, which increased market share, partly
reflected market new commercial strategy of offering a more diversified tyre
range.
Michelin has also seen strong demand for 'green' tyres, which reduce fuel
consumption by lowering resistance with the road. Michelin described the
tyres as the most important technological innovation since its development
of the radial tyre. It aims to produce about 14m green tyres this year.
A FFr2.5bn exceptional charge relating to restructuring was the principal
factor in the large loss in the first half last year. But even stripping out
exceptional charges, Michelin achieved a net profit of FFr732m against a
loss of FFr827m in the 1993 half of 1993.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
