<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 94 / International Company News: First Financial wins Western
Union auction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEWARK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
First Financial Management, a data processing company, has won the bidding
for Western Union, the world's biggest non-bank money transfer company, with
a Dollars 1.153bn offer, a US bankruptcy court judge said yesterday, Reuter
reports from Newark.
Western Union, which was put up for auction by the bankruptcy judge in June,
though not itself in bankruptcy, is owned by New Valley, which has been
operating under Chapter 11 of the US bankruptcy code since March.
Atlanta-based First Financial Management's winning bid beat that of its
rival Forstmann Little, a leveraged buy-out firm, which dropped out of the
bidding at Dollars 1.143bn.
The third bidder, First Data, a credit card processing company spun off by
American Express two years ago, also dropped out of the bidding.
Bankruptcy Judge Novalyn Winfield said: 'Well, this long process is over and
the marketplace seems to have won. This seems to be the highest and best
offer for the company.'
Mr Carl Icahn, who owns about Dollars 80m worth of New Valley bonds, said:
'This open bidding is terrific. I think it should be adopted in other
bankruptcy cases.'
He said he bought the bonds at 20 cents to 30 cents on the dollar and would
be repaid in full.
</TEXT>
