<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC2 presents an 'Education Special' called Simple Minds based on recent
Harvard University research which shows that much science teaching is
hopelessly misconceived. Children, as we should all know, having been
children, do not have empty 'simple minds' into which logical concepts can
be poured; they have their own ideas about the world around them and how it
works, ideas that are often at odds with scientific explanations (7.20
BBC2). Cookery programmes are old hat. Now you have to do 'lifestyle' or
'culture' series, which means lots of travel and folksy wisdom, and precious
few recipes. In the first of Raymond's Blanc Mange we are told that Martin
Jarvis plays Brillat-Savarin. Oh dear (8.30 BBC2). In Trial And Error David
Jessel suggests that Sheila Bowler is serving a life sentence for the murder
ofher aunt because her unemotional manner convinced police of her guilt. He
maintains that her alleged motive would have been rejected by any crime
fiction writer as being on the thin side (9.00 C4). C4 begins 704 Hauser
Street, a latterday 'All In The Family' (11.50).
</TEXT>
