<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 94 / Lecturers quit pay talks with colleges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Talks between lecturers at further education colleges and their employers
over new contracts broke down again yesterday, with unions accusing college
principals of 'contemptuous' gestures.
The National Association of Teachers in Further and Higher Education said it
had abandoned national discussions, and wanted lecturers to 'go on the
offensive locally'. Its dispute started with the attempted introduction of
new contracts last June. National talks restarted only last week after a gap
of six months.
The union said that the only offer made by the Colleges' Employers' Forum,
which has represented most colleges since they were removed from local
authority control in April last year, was to put a limit of 1,000 hours on
teaching time each year. The current maximum is 756 hours.
Mr John Akker, the union's general secretary, said: 'An enormous opportunity
has been lost and I am bitterly disappointed. The Colleges' Employers' Forum
does not appear to understand either the job of lecturers or the concept of
negotiation.'
Mr Roger Ward, forum chief executive, said lecturers offering higher
education or A-level courses would not be required to work more than 800
hours.
He added: 'Since the beginning of this dispute, regrettably, the lay
leadership of Natfhe has never produced one sensible proposal. If the
full-time officers cared to put forward a proposal I would willingly examine
it.'
</TEXT>
