<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 94 / Health company to spend Pounds 41m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Smith &amp; Nephew, the healthcare company, is to spend Pounds 41.3m on
redeveloping its medical division's Hull site.
The project, the largest single capital investment in the company's 138-year
history, is intended to increase the division's capacity substantially and
upgrade manufacturing facilities to keep pace with increasingly stringent
international healthcare regulations.
Although Smith &amp; Nephew originated in Hull and has two of its world centres
of excellence there, the company considered focusing the investment
overseas, which would have led to the gradual rundown of the Hull site where
1,200 are employed.
Mr Nick Hildyard, medical division managing director, said the Department of
Trade and Industry's offer of a Pounds 2.65m regional selective assistance
grant helped 'tip the balance' in Hull's favour. The city has Intermediate
Area status, the lower of the two grades on the DTI's regional aid map.
Mr Hildyard said Britain, while fighting hard for inward investment, had
sometimes not put enough effort into retaining investment by home-grown
companies. 'What people have perhaps missed in the hype is the leakage to
overseas locations of UK businesses,' he said.
The Hull site makes advanced wound-care products, using film, foam and gel
technology, and casting and support products for broken and damaged limbs.
Mr Hildyard said Smith &amp; Nephew was the world leader - based on market share
 -in casting and support and in the top three in wound care.
The Hull site's target is 10 per cent a year growth in volume over the next
five years through the development of new markets and new products. The
company hopes increased sales stemming from the new investment will boost
employment at Hull to 1,300 by the year 2000. Construction starts in
January.
Medical division sales have doubled in the past five years to nearly Pounds
200m. Two-thirds of products made in Hull are exported to more than 120
countries worldwide.
Mrs Maureen Foers, president of Hull Chamber of Commerce and Shipping,
welcomed the news. She said: 'If Smith &amp; Nephew have the confidence in Hull
to make this sort of investment other organisations should look very
closely.'
</TEXT>
