<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 94 / The Liberal Democrats in Brighton: Party's tax strategy
thrown into confusion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Liberal Democrats' attempts to formulate a distinctive tax policy were
thrown into confusion yesterday as the newly-appointed Treasury spokesman
appeared to overturn key planks in the party's latest tax and benefit
proposals.
In a conference presentation designed to cast the Liberal Democrats as a
party of low rather than high taxation, Mr Malcolm Bruce rejected a plan
from its policymaking committee to back an increase in the top rate of
income tax to 60 per cent. Instead he proposed that no one should pay a
marginal rate of above 50 per cent.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, the party leader, favours a 50 per cent rate, but senior
party figures are not sure whether the conference will insist on the higher
level in a debate today.
Mr Bruce produced an eye-catching proposal to introduce a 10 per cent
income-tax band for the lower paid, compensated for in part by the
introduction of a range of environmental taxes. He said the party would seek
to take many people out of taxation by raising thresholds.
He cast doubt on a range of specific commitments in last month's policy
document - Opportunity and Independence for All - to raise child benefit by
up to Pounds 5 per week, increase in-work benefits, and provide higher
payments to the the young unemployed. Mr Bruce said all spending pledges
would be subject to a rigorous costing programme before the next general
election.
But amid confusion among delegates and some MPs about the party's tax
strategy, Mr Bruce backed plans to raise the earnings ceiling on National
Insurance contributions, a move which would raise by 10 per cent the
marginal tax rate of those on middle incomes.
Mr Bruce first suggested that those affected would be compensated by cuts in
income tax as the two systems were integrated. But he then raised the
possibility that the NIC ceiling might be kept in place. Admitting that the
party's present stance might lack 'clarity', he said that by the time of the
next general election it would produce a fully costed, itemised tax and
spending programme.
Among the new environmental taxes proposed by the party are a carbon tax
along the lines of that proposed by the European Commission, the
introduction of road pricing, a greenfield development tax, a levy on
agricultural fertilisers and pesticides and on packaging.
Mr Bruce said the money raised would be used to cut taxes elsewhere, but the
party committed itself earlier this month to using some of the income to
increase public spending.
</TEXT>
