<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 94 / The Liberal Democrats in Brighton: Activists reject idea of
pacts with Blair
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Liberal Democrat activists yesterday warned the leadership they would not
tolerate pre-election deals with Labour.
Amid growing controversy over the decision by senior party figures to
abandon the policy of 'equidistance' from Labour and the Tories, delegates
made clear that their implacable opposition to the present government could
not be the precursor to an electoral pact with Mr Tony Blair, the new Labour
leader.
In spite of Mr Paddy Ashdown's refusal to join the debate, four members of
his Westminster team yesterday joined those who ruled out sustaining the
Conservatives in office after a general election.
Mr Menzies Campbell, Mr Alan Beith, Sir Russell Johnston and Mr Alex Carlile
said it was inconceivable that the party could prop up a minority Tory
government.
But senior party figures bowed to grassroots pressure to dismiss any idea of
a pre-election deal with Labour.
At a fringe meeting yesterday several delegates were warmly applauded after
voicing animosity to Labour politicians on local councils.
There was little support for senior party figures - including Baroness
Williams and Lord Jenkins - who have openly supported Mr Blair's election as
leader.
The overwhelming majority of voters think the Liberal Democrats' policies
are closer to Labour's than the Tories', says an opinion poll for BBC's
Newsnight and The Independent.
The poll of more than 1,100 voters throughout Britain found people no longer
see the Liberal Democrats as 'equidistant' from Labour and the
Conservatives. But a majority of supporters of both opposition parties
oppose a pre-election pact against the Tories.
</TEXT>
