<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 94 / Tawdry Trocadero rescued yet again: The troubles of a 'very
1970s' shopping complex in central London
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Located just off London's Piccadilly Circus, one of the world's busiest
tourist thoroughfares, the Trocadero leisure and shopping centre attracts
16m visitors a year.
About half of them, however, spend no money there. The vast majority of
visitors stay for less than 30 minutes.
On a rainy afternoon it is not hard to see why. The Trocadero, off
Piccadilly Circus, is a tawdry and gloomy place.
In its shabby food hall yesterday the toilets were closed and staff at a
sushi bar were arguing with a customer about whether he had paid for his
food.
Today the Trocadero acquires its fourth owner in 10 years. Burford, the
property group, has acquired the centre from receivers KPMG Peat Marwick for
Pounds 94m.
Mr Nick Leslau, Burford's chief executive, plans to turn the Trocadero into
an 'urban theme park'. It will, he says, become Europe's leading
high-technology leisure centre.
Burford is negotiating with companies interested in renting the 120,000 sq
ft of vacant space at the Trocadero - about a quarter of total space.
Companies involved in the negotiations are believed to include Sega
Enterprises, the Japanese maker of electronic games, which could build an
electronic theme park in the centre.
Mr Leslau agrees that in its current state the Trocadero is 'tired'. He
adds: 'It feels very 1970s. It lacks direction.'
He insists, however, that the Trocadero should be successful. It stands on
one of the world's busiest streets, between Piccadilly Circus and Leicester
Square. About 75 per cent of the 20m foreign tourists who come to the UK
each year visit the area. Half the Trocadero's visitors are tourists.
By the time Burford has finished its Pounds 10m to Pounds 12m refurbishment
of the centre it will feel like something out of the 21st century, he says.
'It's going to have this buzz of people walking along aerial walkways and
elevators.'
Burford is respected in the City as a conservatively-managed property group.
With the Trocadero, however, it is attempting to succeed where others have
failed.
In the 1920s two restaurants opened on the site, the Trocadero and a Lyons
Corner House. Lyons, which operated both, sold the buildings in the 1950s,
after which the area steadily deteriorated.
In 1984 the Trocadero reopened as a shopping and entertainment centre, under
the ownership of Electricity Supply Nominees, the pension fund of the
electricity supply industry. The project was plagued by cost overruns.
In 1987 Brent Walker, the leisure group, teamed up with Power Corporation,
the Irish property group, to buy the Trocadero. Both companies suffered
financial damage as a result of the purchase. At the beginning of last year
the centre went into receivership. The receivers have won several new
tenants including the Planet Hollywood restaurant.
Staff at the existing attractions, such as the Guinness World of Records
exhibition and Emaginator, a simulated train ride, appear cheerful and
well-trained. Mr Leslau accepts that service throughout the centre will have
to improve.
He says Burford has the advantage of having paid a realistic price. At the
height of the property boom the Trocadero was valued at Pounds 250m.
</TEXT>
