<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 94 / Timber groups attack grant scheme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A grant scheme for tree planting was criticised by timber groups yesterday
for failing to provide enough incentives for new land or money to be put
into forestry.
The Forestry Commission scheme is part of government efforts to boost
production of conifers for timber and improve woodland management.
The scheme involves an increase of at least 10 per cent in funding, although
the total has not yet been agreed with the Treasury.
Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary, said the scheme particularly aimed to
ensure a steady supply of softwood for UK timber processing in the next
century. New conifer planting has fallen from 25,000 hectares a year to
about 10,500 hectares since the abolition of controversial tax incentives in
1988. Britain produces only about 14 per cent of its timber needs.
Under the scheme the grant for new conifer plantations increases to Pounds
700 a hectare, up from Pounds 615 for plantings of 10 hectares or more.
Farmers will be encouraged to turn surplus arable or grassland over to
conifers with a Pounds 200 a hectare increase in special grants for this
purpose to Pounds 600.
To improve existing woodland, the commission is offering discretionary
payments for work that leads to 'significant environmental benefits'. There
is also a new annual grant of Pounds 80 a hectare for farmers who promote
regeneration of woodland by preventing grazing.
The Timber Growers' Association, which represents woodland owners and
forestry businesses, said the package amounted to 'tinkering' rather than a
successful forestry strategy.
The association also expressed disappointment at the absence of moves to
widen forestry ownership by making it possible to buy shares in a forestry
investment scheme rather than having to buy a whole forest.
</TEXT>
<XX>
