<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 94 / Threat of strike at BT recedes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The executive of the National Communications Union is today expected to
retreat from industrial conflict with British Telecommunications over new
working patterns.
BT and the union have been in negotiation for several months about new
working patterns designed to ensure that more staff are available to
customers at weekends and in the evenings.
It appeared that negotiations had broken down after nearly three-quarters of
the 27,000 affected workers rejected the changes in a ballot.
However it now appears that sufficient common ground has been found for a
deal. A joint statement issued yesterday said: 'Both BT and the NCU believe
that they have identified the basis for a joint agreement on CSIP (Customer
Service Improvement Programme) attendance patterns.
'BT is prepared to defer commencement of phase 2 until 26 September in order
to establish whether we are jointly able to confirm that there are no
differences between the company and the NCU executive.'
The reason for the change of heart on both sides may be found in the number
of employees who had signed up voluntarily for one of the four new
attendance patterns in spite of a recommendation from the union not to do
so.
It is thought that about 40 per cent of the 27,000 workers have signed up.
That is more than the union would have liked and would have made industrial
action difficult to sustain.
But equally, a clear majority of staff have followed the union instruction -
in spite of strong pressure from managers to accept the deal - which might
have made life difficult for BT.
Under the most radical work pattern options, staff can work regular weekends
in return for a four or even three-day week and a Pounds 1,000 one-off
payment. BT also says that the options are voluntary and staff can opt to
remain on their existing hours. The voluntary status of the agreement has,
however, been questioned by some staff and union officials.
</TEXT>
