<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 94 / Number of new students may fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The number of students enrolling at UK universities this year is likely to
fall slightly compared with last year - after more than a decade of
continuous expansion - according to the Universities Central Admissions
System, John Authers writes.
Today is the deadline for new applicants to the clearing system. About
265,000 people have accepted places compared with the target of 270,000,
achieved last year. But the number of 18-year-olds has fallen by 4 per cent
so acceptances have risen as a proportion of the age group.
So far 33,600 have been accepted through the clearing system for those who
did not satisfy offers conditional on gaining specific grades in A-level
exams, compared with 35,600 at the same point last year. Admissions officers
report a dramatic slackening of interest, particularly in science and modern
languages.
Mr Tony Higgins, Ucas chief executive, said these figures might overstate
the shortfall, as they took no account of people who 'literally come in off
the street and apply direct to one university'. This practice is
particularly common at London's former polytechnics.
He attributed the slight fall in demand to the economic recovery, which had
cut the number of mature students.
</TEXT>
