<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 94 / Halifax raises interest rates to borrowers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Halifax Building Society, the UK's biggest mortgage lender, yesterday raised
the standard variable interest rate it charges borrowers by 0.46 percentage
points, taking it to 8.1 per cent.
Interest-rate movements have often given financial institutions an
opportunity to widen their interest margins, but the competitive pressure on
organisations to pass on higher interest rates to investors was underlined
yesterday as National Savings announced a new issue of higher returns on its
fixed-rate products. Its variable rate products remain unchanged.
National Savings' response to the 0.5 percentage points increase in base
interest rates last Monday includes the pensioners' guaranteed income bond,
which was launched in last year's Budget. The bond was seen by societies as
partly responsible for the net outflows of retail deposits suffered early
this year.
Halifax has not yet announced the new rates it plans to offer on its savings
accounts but said it would 'pass on whatever we can to our savers'. The
society's results for the six months to the end of July showed that, like
others in the sector, its margins had narrowed since last year.
The increase in the rate paid by most of Halifax's 1.8m borrowers is the
biggest yet by a lender in response to last week's increase in base rates,
and is set to trigger rises from other lenders in the coming days.
The society withdrew its range of fixed-rate mortgages last week and is not
currently offering fixed-rate home loans.
Barclays Bank also announced an increase yesterday - of 0.36 percentage
points, taking its standard variable rate to 8.1 per cent. Last week it
announced a rise of 0.5 percentage points in some of its savings rates.
Abbey National, the home loans and banking group, and Nationwide Building
Society, the UK's second biggest society, raised their mortgage rates last
Monday - by smaller percentages than Halifax, but from the higher base of
7.74 per cent.
At 7.64 per cent the standard variable rate offered by Halifax was among the
most competitive on offer. It acknowledged that the next move in interest
rates would be upwards but said there was no need for sharp increases and
suggestions of steep rises were damaging for confidence.
It said: 'To see speculation about rates in double figures does nobody any
good.' So far, however, last week's rise had had only a 'minimal impact' on
the housing market.
Other lenders have, however, expressed greater concern about the adverse
effect of the rise, particularly given its timing at the start of the
important autumn sales period.
Monthly mortgage lending figures have given a picture of a fragile and
uncertain recovery in the housing market over the summer.
</TEXT>
