<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 94 / Labour calls for shake-up of City regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour yesterday called for an overhaul of the UK's financial regulatory
system following the decision by the European Commission of Human Rights to
refer the case of Mr Ernest Saunders, the former Guinness chairman, to the
Human Rights Court.
Mr Saunders was jailed for his role in the Guinness takeover of Distillers.
The European Commission has supported his claim that the government's
handling of the inquiry was a breach of his human rights.
Mr Alistair Darling, Labour's City spokesman, said: 'The European ruling on
the Saunders' case gives rise to general concern that this is just the
latest of a long line of problems which has called into question the ability
of the UK to police City crime.'
He also said the revelations in the Financial Times concerning Lord Archer's
dealing in Anglia Television shares - which have been the subject of a
Department of Trade and Industry investigation - 'undermines the system for
dealing with insider dealing'.
Directors of Anglia were warned in writing almost two years ago that neither
they nor their spouses should deal in the company's shares in January or
February, which is when Lord Archer subsequently placed the share orders.
Labour is calling on the government to introduce new legislation in this
parliamentary session. Mr Darling has outlined four demands:
A reformed and strengthened Securities and Investments Board along the lines
of the US Securities and Exchange Commission, allowing regulators to
investigate allegations of insider dealing and prevent wrongdoers from
trading.
An examination of the way City fraud cases are prosecuted, including the
role of the Serious Fraud Office.
The publication of DTI investigations into politicians and the establishment
of an impartial body to decide whether to proceed with prosecution.
An end to self-regulation to restore confidence in direct regulation under
the SIB.
Mr Darling said: 'At the moment there is little chance of City crime being
detected, even less chance of prosecution, and those convicted have a good
chance of walking free from court.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
