<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 94 / Warning on Russian inflation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Russian inflation will 'inevitably' rise sharply in the last months of this
year, according to Mr Andrei Illarionov, a former economic adviser to the
prime minister and head of the Institute for Economic Analysis. Mr
Illarionov said it would rise from under 4 per cent in August to 7-8 per
cent in September and move higher in the last three months of the year,
reflecting the steep growth of credits in the summer. Mr Illarionov said
that the government has so far this year issued credits totalling
Rbs25,000bn (Pounds 6.8bn). He said inflation had been kept low because the
velocity of money had fallen - but this could be expected to be temporary.
However, figures produced by the Centre for Economic Performance, headed by
Prof Richard Layard, of the London School of Economics, shows that real
consumption has risen by 10 per cent during the year to July and that the
real income of households has risen by 18 per cent in the same period. Prof
Layard said the recorded fall of 24 per cent of industrial production
compared with a year ago was 'difficult to reconcile with the consumption
data'.
</TEXT>
