<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 94 / Result leaves markets nervous
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Fears that Sweden's new Social Democratic government would not be strong
enough to push through tough spending cuts yesterday alarmed financial
markets.
The weak electoral showing by the Liberal party also disappointed the
markets, where it had been hoped its influence would strengthen the
government's resolve to push through strong measures to tackle Sweden's
yawning budget deficit.
'This is the worst possible scenario,' said Mr Christian Diebitsch, analyst
with Kleinwort Benson in London. 'We have a weak left-wing government which
isn't strong enough to implement spending cuts on its own and a Liberal
party which isn't strong enough to support them.'
He said the market was looking for a budget strengthening package of between
SKr100bn (Pounds 8.3bn) and SKr150bn, compared with the SKr61bn package
outlined by the Social Democrats before the election.
In early market reaction, long-term interest rates rose, share prices
tumbled and the krona weakened, before rallying.
The general stock exchange index closed 0.38 percentage points lower at
1424.9.
</TEXT>
