<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 94 / Rail union backs talks but calls new strikes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The three-month rail dispute edged closer to a settlement last night when
the RMT transport union executive endorsed the call for negotiations made at
the weekend by the union's signal workers' conference. But it also announced
further days for disruption.
Mr Jimmy Knapp, the union's general secretary, said he was contacting the
conciliation service Acas to prepare for talks with Railtrack on a
restructuring package and on the union's claim for past efficiency gains.
'These will be conducted in parallel,' he added. 'We shall be talking to
Acas about the most practical way of making progress'.
The move followed the unanimous weekend decision by signal workers to call
for talks on future restructuring for the first time in the dispute, while
continuing to press their pay claim for past efficiency.
Railtrack, the state-owned company which runs the rail infrastructure, said
it was 'keen to resume talks on restructuring to resolve this damaging
dispute as soon as possible'. The negotiations are likely to start
immediately.
Sir Bob Reid, chairman of British Rail, which operates rail services,
welcomed the RMT executive's decision last night.
'It is a very hopeful sign,' he said. 'This is obviously a delicate stage
and it is important each side enters this with a desire to reach agreement.'
He added: 'The strikes have gone on too long and have caused a lot of
damage. Many jobs are involved and many customers have been seriously
inconvenienced.'
However, the RMT executive also announced that Friday's planned one-day
strike by signal workers would go ahead, and called for a further stoppage
by signalmen from midnight on Wednesday September 28 to midnight on Friday
September 30.
'At this stage it would be premature to consider lifting industrial action,'
said Mr Knapp. Railtrack said it was 'extremely disappointed' that the union
had 'chosen to further threaten the public with two further days of
unnecessary action'.
The RMT executive committee plans to step up the industrial conflict if no
progress is made in the parallel negotiations. The final package will be
presented to the signal workers for their approval in a postal ballot.
In a related development last night the union executive announced a 24-hour
stoppage on the London Underground for September 30 after a postal ballot of
union members rejected a 2.5 per cent pay offer and voted for strike action
by 2,072 with 809 against.
Rail negotiators look for common ground again, Page 10
</TEXT>
