<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / World Bond Markets: New York
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fear of inflation continues to grip the US credit markets. At the end of a
jittery week, bond prices plummeted on Friday after the Federal Reserve
reported bigger than expected increases in August industrial production and
capacity utilisation. The benchmark 30-year long bond sank by 1 19/32 to 96
13/16 , lifting its yield by 12 basis points to nearly 7.8 per cent - the
highest this year.
Most analysts cling to the belief that the Fed will hold off until November
before contemplating another rise in short-term interest rates, but each
time another bout of bad news like Friday's hits the market, investors turn
their thoughts to the possibility that the Fed could move before then -
perhaps as early as its September 27 meeting.
Fortunately, perhaps, the next few days may be relatively quiet in this
respect, since the economic reports due to be published are less closely
watched for signs of incipient inflation than last week's.
On Tuesday, figures for July's trade deficit are expected to show little
change from June's Dollars 9.4bn; on Wednesday, figures for August housing
starts are expected to have slipped a little to an annual rate of 1.4m; and
on Thursday, the federal government is expected to report a budget deficit
of Dollars 24bn for August, putting it on track for a deficit of less than
Dollars 200bn for the year - the lowest since 1989.
